THE BED oF GAUL.

‘ O spread the bed of Gaul, ye sons of the strings, and his sun-beam close by him, where his bed may be marked from afar, though overlhadowed with lofty boughs; under the oak of the greenest blow, that quickest grows, and of the most lasting hue, that pours out her leaves on the breath of the shower, though the field all around be withered. Her leaves, from the utmost bounds, shall be seen by the birds os summer, and every bird, as he comes, alights on the top of the bough os strumen.
